# Partitioning & Bucketing - Complete Interview Answers (1 Block)

```python
# ============================================
# Q1: What is partitioning in Spark?
# ============================================
# Physical folder separation by column value
df.write.partitionBy("year", "month").parquet("/orders")
# Output: /orders/year=2024/month=01/file.parquet

# ============================================
# Q2: What is bucketing in Spark?
# ============================================
# Fixed N files, data distributed by hash(column) % N
df.write.bucketBy(100, "user_id").saveAsTable("orders")
# user_id=123 → bucket 23 (hash(123) % 100), same ID always same bucket

# ============================================
# Q3: Why need these two?
# ============================================
# Partitioning → Partition pruning (skip folders at query time)
# Bucketing → Bucketed joins (NO SHUFFLE), sampling, pre-shuffling

# ============================================
# Q4: When to use Partitioning?
# ============================================
# ✓ Low cardinality (<10k unique values), common WHERE filter, time series
# ✗ High cardinality → folder explosion (NameNode pressure)
df.write.partitionBy("country", "year")  # Good (200 countries × 10 years)

# ============================================
# Q5: When to use Bucketing?
# ============================================
# ✓ High cardinality (millions), frequent JOINs, large tables (100GB+)
df.write.bucketBy(256, "user_id").saveAsTable("large_users")

# ============================================
# Q6: Partition + Bucket together?
# ============================================
df.write.partitionBy("year").bucketBy(128, "user_id").saveAsTable("tbl")
# Partition first (coarse), then bucket inside each partition

# ============================================
# Q7: Optimal number of buckets?
# ============================================
# Rule: 2-4× number of partitions in cluster
# 100 executors → 200-400 buckets (not too many small files)

# ============================================
# Q8: Partition vs Bucket performance difference?
# ============================================
# Partition: WHERE year=2024 → reads 1 folder (100x faster)
# Bucket: JOIN on user_id → 0 shuffle (10x faster)

# ============================================
# Q9: Problems with too many partitions?
# ============================================
# 10,000+ partitions → Slow metadata ops, small files, NameNode memory full

# ============================================
# Q10: Can bucket column be different from partition column?
# ============================================
# Yes. Partition on date (filter), bucket on user_id (join)
df.write.partitionBy("date").bucketBy(256, "user_id")


